  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1170020093" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1170020093" />
    <a title="Kevin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35434974-kevin"><img alt="Kevin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607981917p2/35434974.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1170020093?book_show_action=true">Jan 15, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kevin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kevin" href="/user/show/35434974-kevin">Kevin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9788087830963" href="/book/show/18391731-homage-to-catalonia">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35434974-kevin?shelf=z-fiction">z-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1170020093" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17313476426896075063">[2020 Update of older reviews]: <br/>--Political views need to be constantly tested and updated. Two of my early influences were both great admirers of Orwell: <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2476.Noam_Chomsky' title='Noam Chomsky' rel='nofollow noopener'>Noam Chomsky</a> and <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/3956.Christopher_Hitchens' title='Christopher Hitchens' rel='nofollow noopener'>Christopher Hitchens</a>. <br/>--Chomsky introduced me to <b>anti-imperialism</b> and <b>propaganda</b> (esp. <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/880501.Necessary_Illusions_Thought_Control_in_Democratic_Societies' title='Necessary Illusions Thought Control in Democratic Societies by Noam Chomsky' rel='nofollow noopener'>Necessary Illusions: Thought Control in Democratic Societies</a>). The latter topic should have brought up the following unsettling questions: <i>how do we evaluate liberal imperialist miseducation&apos;s love for Orwell&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/170448.Animal_Farm' title='Animal Farm by George Orwell' rel='nofollow noopener'>Animal Farm</a> and <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40961427.1984' title='1984 by George Orwell' rel='nofollow noopener'>1984</a> (prominen</i></span>
  <span id="freeText17313476426896075063" style="display:none">[2020 Update of older reviews]: <br />--Political views need to be constantly tested and updated. Two of my early influences were both great admirers of Orwell: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2476.Noam_Chomsky" title="Noam Chomsky" rel="nofollow noopener">Noam Chomsky</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/3956.Christopher_Hitchens" title="Christopher Hitchens" rel="nofollow noopener">Christopher Hitchens</a>. <br />--Chomsky introduced me to <b>anti-imperialism</b> and <b>propaganda</b> (esp. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/880501.Necessary_Illusions_Thought_Control_in_Democratic_Societies" title="Necessary Illusions Thought Control in Democratic Societies by Noam Chomsky" rel="nofollow noopener">Necessary Illusions: Thought Control in Democratic Societies</a>). The latter topic should have brought up the following unsettling questions: <i>how do we evaluate liberal imperialist miseducation's love for Orwell's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/170448.Animal_Farm" title="Animal Farm by George Orwell" rel="nofollow noopener">Animal Farm</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40961427.1984" title="1984 by George Orwell" rel="nofollow noopener">1984</a> (prominent in the high school education systems), and how should we position this with Orwell's own views?</i><br />--This question came about slowly for me, as Chomsky himself has been a USSR-basher (<i>"USSR was a dungeon"</i>). But perhaps I was ready to put everyone under the microscope as the crude-Trotskyite Hitchens face-planted into reactionary Islamophobia and outright US imperialist warmongering after 9/11. <br />--The real breakthrough for me came with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/10707.Vijay_Prashad" title="Vijay Prashad" rel="nofollow noopener">Vijay Prashad</a>, who helped me look beyond the West-versus-Soviets Cold War worldview by synthesizing the perspectives from the global South and the process of <b>decolonization</b>. The global South's experiences with colonialism brings different views of Britain (the empire) compared with the USSR (especially the Russian Revolution): <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/M-frUMXKcEw?t=358">https://youtu.be/M-frUMXKcEw?t=358</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38206601.Red_Star_Over_the_Third_World" title="Red Star Over the Third World by Vijay Prashad" rel="nofollow noopener">Red Star Over the Third World</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17609.The_Darker_Nations_A_People_s_History_of_the_Third_World" title="The Darker Nations A People's History of the Third World by Vijay Prashad" rel="nofollow noopener">The Darker Nations: A People's History of the Third World</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3004197.The_Blood_Never_Dried_A_People_s_History_of_the_British_Empire" title="The Blood Never Dried A People's History of the British Empire by John Newsinger" rel="nofollow noopener">The Blood Never Dried: A People's History of the British Empire</a><br />--Thus, Prashad took the propaganda model to another level when considering imperialism's <b>ideological censorship</b>: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/6jKcsHv3c74">https://youtu.be/6jKcsHv3c74</a><br />--Others might have grappled with the contradictions of revolutions and real-world socialism (esp. "<b>Siege Socialism</b>") with the help of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/21234.Michael_Parenti" title="Michael Parenti" rel="nofollow noopener">Michael Parenti</a>: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/O8k0yO-deoA?t=27">https://youtu.be/O8k0yO-deoA?t=27</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/404273.Blackshirts_and_Reds_Rational_Fascism_and_the_Overthrow_of_Communism" title="Blackshirts and Reds Rational Fascism and the Overthrow of Communism by Michael Parenti" rel="nofollow noopener">Blackshirts and Reds: Rational Fascism and the Overthrow of Communism</a><br /><br />--Now, I have little interest in spending so much time on one individual as to become an Orwell historian. It's enough for me to accept that such a prominent political commentator engaged in the messy real world will reflect many contradictions. <br />--I'm willing to take the good: fighting Fascist Franco (this book), reporting on the working conditions of the British working class (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/30553.The_Road_to_Wigan_Pier" title="The Road to Wigan Pier by George Orwell" rel="nofollow noopener">The Road to Wigan Pier</a>) and the precariat (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/393199.Down_and_Out_in_Paris_and_London" title="Down and Out in Paris and London by George Orwell" rel="nofollow noopener">Down and Out in Paris and London</a>). <br />--His earlier excursions in the Indian Imperial Police (fictionalized in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9650.Burmese_Days" title="Burmese Days by George Orwell" rel="nofollow noopener">Burmese Days</a>) I found surprisingly uncompelling. <br />--Besides debates around his famous fictions, another controversy leftists focus on is Orwell's activities with the propaganda unit of imperialist Britain towards the end of his life, with the infamous <b>Orwell's List</b>: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orwell%27s_list">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orwell%...</a> <br />...for more, see Ben Norton's "George Orwell was a reactionary snitch who made a blacklist of leftists for the British government": <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://bennorton.com/george-orwell-list-leftists-snitch-british-government/">https://bennorton.com/george-orwell-l...</a><br /><br /><br />//old review:<br />Here we have socialist Orwell's experience in 1937 Catalonia, where anarchist/anti-Stalin Marxist workers collectivized Barcelona and were running the city (anarcho-syndacalism) during the Spanish Civil War against Fascist Franco. It turns out this type of direct democracy is unacceptable to all vertical power structures, not just Fascists. The Stalinist bureaucracy and Spanish Government, supposed allies in the Civil War, purged these workers. <br /><br />Meanwhile, Western Capitalist "democracies" didn't even bother supporting the fight against Fascism; they were too busy appeasing Hitler (Munich Agreement).<br />*Update: American oil company Texaco (ran by outright Nazi Torkild Rieber) supplied much-needed oil to Fascist Franco.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17313476426896075063" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

